# Selenium Locating Strategies
1️⃣ What are Selenium Locating Strategies?
Selenium locating strategies are methods used to identify and locate web elements on a webpage.
Before performing actions like:
    1. Clicking a button
    2. Entering a text in a box
    3. Selecting a dropdown
    4. Submitting a form

Selenium must find the element in the webpage DOM.
To do this, selenium provides different locator strategies.

2️⃣ Why Locators are Important?
Locators help selenium interact with webpage element.
Without locators selenium cananot perform actions like:
    1. click()
    2. send_keys()
    3. clear()
    4. submit()

Example:   
    element = driver.find_element(By.ID, "username")
    element.send_keys("admin")

Here Selenium first locates the element and then performs an action.

3️⃣ Selenium Provides 7 Locator Strategies
Selenium Provides the following 7 ways to locate elements.
    1️⃣ Locating Element By ID(By.ID)
    The ID attribute uniquely identifies an element in a webpage
    Because ID is unique, it is fastest and more reliable locator.
    Example HTML:
        <input type="text" id="username">
    
    Selenium Code:
        byId=driver.find_element(By.ID , "username")
    
    Advantages:
    -----------
    1. Fastest locator
    2. Unique element identification
    3. Recommanded whenever available
    
    2️⃣ Element By Class Name(By.CLASS_NAME)
    Class name is used for styling the elements
    Multiple elements can share the same class name
    Example HTML:
        <button class="login-btn">Login</button>
    
    Selenium Code:
        byClassName=driver.find_element(By.CLASS_NAME , "login-btn")
    
    NOTE:
        Class names may not always be unique.

    3️⃣ Locating Element By Name (By.NAME)
    The name attribute commonly used in forms
    Example HTML:
        <input type="text" name="email">
    
    Selenium Code:
        byName= driver.find_element(By.NAME , "email")
    
    Used mostly for:
    ----------------
    1. input fields
    2. radio buttons
    3. form elements

    4️⃣ Locating Element By Tag Name (By.TAG_NAME)
    Every HTML element has a tag name
    Common tags include:
    1. input
    2. div
    3. p
    4. button
    5. select
    
    Example HTML
        <button type="submit" name="login">
    
    Selenium Code:
        byTagName=driver.find_element(By.TAGNAME , "button")
    
    Useful when:
    ------------
    1. Locating multiple elements
    2. Performing operations on groups

    Selenium Code:
        ByTagName=driver.find_elements(By.TAGNAME , "input")
    
    5️⃣ Locating Element By CSS Selector (By.CSS_SELECTOR)
    CSS selectors are patterns used to select HTML elements.
    They are faster than XPATH
    Example HTML
        <div class="title">Welcome</div>
    
    Selenium Code:
    byCssSelector=driver.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR , "div.title")

    Common CSS selectors:
    ---------------------
    Selector & Example
    Tag  -> input
    Class -> .btn
    ID -> #header
    Descendant -> div p

    6️⃣ Locating Element By XPath(By.XPATH)
    XPATH is used to navigate through the HTML DOM structure.
    It can locate elements using:
    1. attributes
    2. relationships
    3. positions
    
    Selenium Code:
        element = driver.find_element(By.XPATH, "//input[@id='username']")
    
    Advantages:
    -----------
    1. Very powe4full
    2. Can locate complex elements

    Disadvantages:
    --------------
    Slighly slower than CSS selectors

    7️⃣ Locating Element By Link Text (By.LINK_TEXT)
    This locator is used to find hyperlinks (<a> tags) using the exact text.
    Example HTML:
        <a href="#">Learn More</a>

    Selenium Code:
        element = driver.find_element(By.LINK_TEXT, "Learn More")


    8️⃣ Locating Element By Partial Link Text
    Used when we only know part of the link text.
    Example HTML:
        <a href="#">Click here to register</a>
    
    Selenium Code:
        element = driver.find_element(By.PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT, "Click")
    
    Useful when:
        1. link text is dynamic
        2. link text is very long
    
    Exception in Locating Elements
    If Selenium cannot find the element , it throws an exception. -> NoSuchElementException
    Example:
        from selenium.common import NoSuchElementException
    
    Best Locator Priority (Recommended Order)
    When writing automation scripts , use locator in this order.
    1. ID
    2. NAME
    3. CSS SELECTOR
    4. XPATH
    5. CLASS NAME
    6. TAG NAME
    7. LINK TEXT

    